§ 176.
Gothic nouns have two numbers—singular and plural;
three genders—masculine, feminine, and neuter, as in the other Old Germanic languages, from which the gender of nouns in Gothic does not materially differ;
four cases—Nominative, Accusative, Genitive, and Dative.
The Vocative is mostly like the Nominative, but in the singular of some classes of nouns it regularly fell together with the Accusative, see §§ 87–8.

Note.—
It should be noted that what is called the dat. sing. in Gothic is originally the instrumental in the a-stems (§ 179) and masc. i-stems (§ 196);
locative in the fem. i- (§ 198), u- (§ 202), and all consonant-stems (§§ 207–22); and the dat. only in the ō-stems (§ 190).

