manna generalized the weak stem-form man-n- which originally belonged only to the gen. dat. sing. and to all forms of the pl. except the nom. (§ 206), cp. the similar levelling in Latin in caro, flesh, acc. carnem, gen. carnis, dat. carnī, nom. pl. carnēs, beside homo, man, hominem, hominis, hominī, nom. pl. hominēs.
Sing. nom. manna for *mana;
acc. mannan for *manan;
gen. mans from *man-n-iz, for *manins,
dat. mann from *manni, for *manin;
Pl. nom. mannans for *manans from *mananiz, mans from *man-n-iz, gen. mannē like aúhsnē (§ 206), dat. mannam formed like han-am (§ 207).
The acc. pl. is the nom. used for the accusative.
In the gen. sing. and nom. acc. pl. the -nnz was simplified to -ns after the loss of the -i- (§ 158 note).

